I work in the legal department of the
Israeli consulate in New York.

44:15.320 --> 44:17.311
-Really? No kidding.
-Mmm.

44:17.739 --> 44:21.152
You're Israeli?
That's funny, you don't sound Israeli.

44:22.076 --> 44:23.452
-l'm not.
-Oh.

44:24.912 --> 44:26.652
Where is your family from?

44:26.748 --> 44:28.079
Excuse me?

44:28.166 --> 44:32.580
Where are you from? Where were you born?
How did you end up here? You know.

44:35.173 --> 44:37.835
Um, I'm from Geneva. Originally.

44:37.925 --> 44:39.335
Really? Geneva.

44:39.427 --> 44:42.419
Any connection to Julian Green?
From Basel?

44:43.139 --> 44:44.174
No.

44:44.265 --> 44:47.598
No? Well, he's a big supporter
of the Israel Museum.

44:48.144 --> 44:50.510
Could I introduce you to him some time?

44:51.773 --> 44:53.638
You want to sit here?

44:53.900 --> 44:58.485
If you want to? I mean, you got work to do,
I'm not gonna bother you. I promise.

44:58.571 --> 44:59.936
It's all right.

45:13.461 --> 45:15.417
NORMAN: Can I ask you something?

45:16.130 --> 45:18.621
What is it you actually deal with?

45:20.802 --> 45:23.794
Like commerce agreements or...

45:23.888 --> 45:25.924
That's a different department.

45:26.015 --> 45:29.553
We're an arm of the Israeli Justice Ministry
in the United States.

45:29.977 --> 45:36.689
Oh. Okay, so if an Israeli criminal
flees to the US,

45:36.776 --> 45:39.142
it's yourjob to bring him back?

45:39.320 --> 45:41.527
-We would be involved in that, yeah.
-Yeah.

45:41.614 --> 45:45.653
The same if an American criminal
tries to hide out in Israel.

45:45.743 --> 45:47.279
Yeah, that, too.

45:48.496 --> 45:51.329
You must have some
really interesting stories.

45:51.999 --> 45:54.035
Like, you know, those Russian oligarchs.

45:54.127 --> 45:57.085
They're wanted all over the world,
but they're looking for asylum in Israel.

45:57.171 --> 46:00.413
Can you give me the inside story
on how that whole thing works?

46:01.008 --> 46:02.168
Sorry.

46:14.522 --> 46:16.058
Do you know Carol Raskin?

46:16.649 --> 46:19.937
You know, I may be wrong about this,
but I think she's actually the one who wrote

46:20.027 --> 46:22.404
a lot of those international treaties
they're talking about.

46:22.488 --> 46:24.865
She's a very close friend of mine.

46:25.867 --> 46:27.732
I'd be very happy to introduce you to her.

46:27.827 --> 46:29.363
No, no, no. That's not necessary.

46:29.454 --> 46:30.944
I wouldn't want to bother her.

46:38.212 --> 46:39.952
You have a family? Kids?

46:42.175 --> 46:43.915
-Family?
-l'm sorry. What?

46:44.010 --> 46:46.092
Do you have a family? Kids?

46:50.099 --> 46:51.430
A partner.

46:54.729 --> 46:56.344
You're a lesbian?

46:57.899 --> 46:59.810
-Yeah?
-(CHUCKLES) Yes. lam.

47:00.151 --> 47:01.357
(LAUGHS)

47:01.444 --> 47:04.527
That's great! Good for you. That's terrific.

47:05.239 --> 47:06.740
-What is?
-No, it's just wonderful.

47:06.824 --> 47:08.655
I love that,
when people know what they want.

47:08.743 --> 47:10.324
You know, and theyjust... (BLOWS)

47:10.411 --> 47:11.821
No, it's a good thing.

47:11.913 --> 47:15.155
I have a very close friend, a rabbi,
professor Nathaniel Lewis,

47:15.249 --> 47:16.864
he teaches at JTS.

47:16.959 --> 47:21.202
His daughter started a
Jewish lesbian organization.

47:21.297 --> 47:23.379
Abigail Lewis. Do you know her?

47:23.466 --> 47:24.501
No.

47:24.592 --> 47:27.254
No? No? She's a... You would love her.

47:27.345 --> 47:29.006
She's a wonderful, wonderful person.

47:29.096 --> 47:31.553
I'd be happy to put the two of you together.

47:33.476 --> 47:36.309
Look, it's the third time in five minutes

47:36.395 --> 47:40.434
that you've tried to introduce me to someone.

47:41.317 --> 47:43.979
Why are you trying to get me to meet people?

47:44.070 --> 47:45.685
Do I look lonely?

47:47.823 --> 47:50.360
Look, I'm sorry.
I didn't want to embarrass you.

47:50.451 --> 47:52.442
If I did that, I apologize.

47:54.539 --> 47:56.951
I appreciate you trying to help connect me.

47:57.041 --> 47:59.453
It's just that I don't need,
uh, connections now.

47:59.669 --> 48:02.502
Okay. So what do you need?

48:05.424 --> 48:06.925
-What do I need?
-Yeah.

48:07.009 --> 48:08.419
I'm offering my services.

48:08.511 --> 48:10.923
What do you need? I'll help you get it.

48:12.515 --> 48:16.679
I need many things, but not
necessarily things you can help me with.

48:17.812 --> 48:19.143
Try me.

48:28.197 --> 48:32.406
I need the satisfaction of knowing
that I'm doing good in the world.

48:34.078 --> 48:35.318
(INHALES DEEPLY)

48:38.082 --> 48:39.697
That's a big one.

48:40.876 --> 48:41.865
You win.

48:42.003 --> 48:43.163
(SCOFFS)

48:45.840 --> 48:47.125
(CHUCKLES)

48:48.509 --> 48:49.794
What about you?

48:50.303 --> 48:52.259
Do you have family? Kids?

48:53.014 --> 48:54.550
Yeah, I have a daughter.

48:54.640 --> 48:57.052
-She just finished graduate school.
-Oh.

48:57.143 --> 48:59.225
Yeah. Yeah, thank you.

48:59.312 --> 49:00.552
Yeah.

49:00.646 --> 49:03.183
Her mother died when she was three.

49:05.401 --> 49:07.266
Sorry to hear that.

49:07.361 --> 49:09.818
So you raised your daughter alone?

49:11.782 --> 49:14.444
I did the best I could, yeah.

49:17.330 --> 49:19.321
And why were you at the convention?

49:19.415 --> 49:22.077
I noticed you were speaking
with the Prime Minister.

49:22.168 --> 49:23.578
You know him well?

49:25.713 --> 49:28.500
Yes. Yes. I do.

49:34.513 --> 49:36.299
How did you meet him?

49:37.099 --> 49:38.305
(SIGHS)

49:40.102 --> 49:42.354
I bought him a pair of shoes.

49:42.688 --> 49:44.599
(SCOFFS) What?
You bought him a pair of shoes?

49:44.690 --> 49:45.930
You never know.

49:46.025 --> 49:49.483
(SING-SONG)
You never know, you never know.

49:51.030 --> 49:52.611
What do you mean
you bought him a pair of shoes?

49:52.698 --> 49:54.404
(IN NORMAL VOICE)
You never know.

49:56.327 --> 49:58.238
A pair of shoes.

49:59.580 --> 50:02.993
The most expensive shoes in all of New York,

50:03.084 --> 50:07.327
but the best investment I made my whole life.

50:14.387 --> 50:17.220
May I ask what you do for a living?

50:17.306 --> 50:19.262
Sure. I'm a businessman.

50:19.350 --> 50:22.092
Oh. What sort of business?

50:23.396 --> 50:26.229
Um, consulting. Mostly.

50:29.151 --> 50:30.937
Who do you consult?

50:31.278 --> 50:36.147
Well, businesses, organizations, individuals.
It varies, you know.

50:37.868 --> 50:40.530
Sometimes I consult other consultants.

50:44.291 --> 50:47.328
But do you have a specific area of expertise?

50:47.962 --> 50:50.874
Can you explain to me
how your business works?

50:50.965 --> 50:53.798
If it is not too complicated. I'm curious.

51:09.066 --> 51:10.522
(INAUDIBLE)

51:52.067 --> 51:53.056
(CAMERA CLICKS)

52:41.367 --> 52:42.903
(LINE RINGING)

52:51.168 --> 52:52.157
NORMAN: Hello?

52:53.045 --> 52:56.583
Hi. It's Alex. From the train just now.

52:58.384 --> 53:00.670
Alex. I was just getting into a cab.

53:00.761 --> 53:02.752
Should I give you a ride? Where are you?

53:04.390 --> 53:06.426
I'm still at Penn Station.

53:11.939 --> 53:13.850
Are you on the street?

53:17.403 --> 53:19.268
No. I'm still inside.

53:23.951 --> 53:27.443
I just realized
you didn't have my telephone number.

53:28.372 --> 53:30.704
So ljust wanted you to have it.

53:31.041 --> 53:33.293
(NORMAN BREATHING HEAVILY)

53:36.589 --> 53:38.580
Norman, are you okay?

53:39.133 --> 53:42.375
Yes, of course I am.
No. Everything is perfect.

53:42.761 --> 53:46.128
Couldn’t be better. No.
This whole evening has been like...

53:46.223 --> 53:48.384
Been like floating on a cloud.

53:48.475 --> 53:51.217
WOMAN ON PA: May I have your attention,
please, Amtrak passengers?

53:51.312 --> 53:53.223
All ticketed passengers

53:53.314 --> 53:57.557
are required to have valid identiﬁcation
at all times.

53:57.651 --> 54:01.815
Randomly selected passengers,
their baggage, handbags...

54:02.990 --> 54:04.355
(SIGHS)

54:05.367 --> 54:07.528
Everybody, go home. Go to sleep.

54:07.620 --> 54:09.906
The historical bond between
the United States and Israel

54:09.997 --> 54:12.613
has never been stronger, you can all relax.

54:13.083 --> 54:14.823
At least till tomorrow morning. Right, Duby?

54:14.919 --> 54:17.501
If I have to shake one more hand tonight,
my fingers will fall off.

54:18.005 --> 54:19.666
One more hand to shake, I'm afraid.

54:19.757 --> 54:22.248
Bruce Schwartz.
Special Middle East Coordinator.

54:22.343 --> 54:23.799
It's good to finally meet in person,
Prime Minister.

54:23.886 --> 54:24.921
We don't have to shake hands.

54:25.012 --> 54:26.377
You're not going to make me
put on my shoes, are you?

54:26.472 --> 54:29.430
No. No. No. This is as informal as could be.

54:29.516 --> 54:32.007
Good. The formal me needs a rest.

54:32.102 --> 54:33.478
Bruce would like to go over some points

54:33.562 --> 54:35.769
before tomorrow's meeting
with the President.

54:35.856 --> 54:37.972
Well, it's less about
your meeting with the President

54:38.067 --> 54:40.023
and more about the statements
you will be delivering

54:40.110 --> 54:41.145
elsewhere around town.

54:41.236 --> 54:43.978
Now, as someone who occupies
a fairly tough job himself...

54:44.073 --> 54:45.529
ESHEL: Excuse me, let me stop you. Please.

54:45.616 --> 54:48.232
Tell the President that
I am here to say "yes" to peace.

54:48.327 --> 54:50.693
I'm sorry "state of peace",
as we agreed to call it.

54:50.788 --> 54:54.246
I fully accept his vision.
I understand it and I believe in it.

54:54.333 --> 54:57.951
No internal politics will change
my commitment to the Wye document.

54:58.212 --> 55:00.373
This evening I had to, uh...

55:01.507 --> 55:03.247
How do you say, uh, mas sefataim?

55:03.550 --> 55:05.677
-To pay lip service.
-Yeah, I had to pay lip service

55:05.761 --> 55:10.721
to a few organizations on a few minor issues,
but I promise you, it has no substance.

55:11.141 --> 55:12.881
BRUCE: Well, I'm sure the President
will be very...

55:12.977 --> 55:15.093
You know what I've found out
in the last couple of weeks

55:15.187 --> 55:16.393
since I was elected?

55:16.480 --> 55:19.688
-Maybe the President can identify with me.
-(CHUCKLING)

55:19.775 --> 55:22.141
For the first time,
I don't have political worries.

55:22.236 --> 55:26.980
Somehow, God put me in this job.

55:27.074 --> 55:29.656
It's not that I didn't work very hard
to get here, I did,

55:29.743 --> 55:33.952
but hundreds of other potential leaders
worked and campaigned just as hard as I did,

55:34.039 --> 55:37.531
and for some reason,
I'm the one sitting in this chair today.

55:37.626 --> 55:41.210
The top spot.
I've reached the top of the ladder.

55:41.714 --> 55:43.545
Why me and not someone else? (SCOFFS)

55:43.632 --> 55:46.624
Who knows?
Believe me, I'm as surprised as anyone else.

55:46.719 --> 55:48.459
But this is the interesting thing,

55:48.554 --> 55:52.297
instead of feeling the burden
of that great responsibility,

55:52.850 --> 55:54.636
I'm feeling...

55:56.020 --> 55:57.009
How do you say goral?

55:57.479 --> 55:59.470
-Fate.
-Fate. I feel fate.

56:00.232 --> 56:03.895
If God put me here,
he must have had a good reason.

56:04.445 --> 56:06.606
Now, I'm not free to run away from this job,

56:06.697 --> 56:09.109
but to be honest,
no single human being can really claim

56:09.199 --> 56:10.814
to be big enough for this job either.

56:10.909 --> 56:13.036
I would be very happy
to go over our itinerary...

56:13.120 --> 56:15.486
What is it that really worries the President?
Tell me.

56:16.457 --> 56:18.448
What doesn't he want me to say?

56:19.084 --> 56:22.076
Well, you have been saying
different things in different forums.

56:22.171 --> 56:24.378
And I think we're just trying
to get a better understanding

56:24.465 --> 56:27.502
of what is the singular message
you wish to deliver.

56:28.594 --> 56:30.459
Oh, the "singular message"?

56:31.597 --> 56:33.133
(CHUCKLES)

56:33.640 --> 56:35.380
You were there tonight, right?

56:35.476 --> 56:39.389
Hanna? Hanna, how many
completely opposing organization leaders

56:39.480 --> 56:41.641
came up to me and said, "We're behind you"?

56:42.441 --> 56:44.056
Fifty? 100?

56:44.151 --> 56:47.063
Each with a completely different agenda.

56:47.488 --> 56:50.605
There is no such thing
as a singular message.

56:50.699 --> 56:52.940
And anyone who tells you
he's got a singular message

56:53.035 --> 56:55.947
is probably teaching at a university
or writing a blog.

56:56.038 --> 56:59.656
-Okay, I didn't mean it that way, I'm sorry...
-I'Il tell you what my singular message is.

56:59.750 --> 57:01.741
I'm going to end this conflict.

57:01.835 --> 57:04.668
How? I'm going to say "yes" to compromise.

57:04.755 --> 57:06.620
To everybody!

57:08.050 --> 57:10.587
Because the opposite of compromise
is not idealism.

57:10.677 --> 57:13.805
The opposite of compromise is not integrity.

57:14.098 --> 57:18.432
The opposite of compromise
is fanaticism and death.

57:20.020 --> 57:22.306
Life is compromise.

57:22.397 --> 57:24.683
I not only believe in that, that is who I am.

57:24.775 --> 57:27.482
That is why I'm here, in this position.

57:29.029 --> 57:30.690
(SIGHS)

57:30.864 --> 57:33.480
If it works,

57:33.575 --> 57:37.818
Iwill go down in history
as the leader who ended this epic conflict.

57:39.081 --> 57:43.996
If I'm wrong, and my compromise
leads to another catastrophic bloody war,

57:45.671 --> 57:50.335
I will blame God for giving me a role
I was clearly incapable of performing.

58:04.731 --> 58:05.982
(DOOR CLOSES)

58:15.075 --> 58:16.485
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

58:20.289 --> 58:22.029
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

58:23.917 --> 58:25.123
Oh, look who showed up.

58:25.210 --> 58:27.496
Our savior has finally arrived.

58:27.588 --> 58:29.124
Sorry I'm late.

58:33.594 --> 58:37.382
No reason to kill me.
Can you get rid of the nuts, please?

58:43.270 --> 58:45.602
The situation is very simple.

58:45.689 --> 58:48.806
The National Council
has decided to sell the building.

58:48.901 --> 58:52.064
To be practical, we need to raise
approximately $14 million

58:52.154 --> 58:55.237
to save us from the wrecking ball
and ensure our future here.

58:55.866 --> 58:59.734
Or we start wandering
from one temporary arrangement to another

58:59.828 --> 59:03.195
which, in my humble opinion,
would mean the end of this community.

59:03.290 --> 59:04.700
MAN: Exactly what we talked about before...

59:04.791 --> 59:06.747
Okay. Well, all right, let's not despair.

59:06.835 --> 59:09.542
This is where our friend
Norman Oppenheimer comes in.

59:14.301 --> 59:15.507
Norman?

59:19.723 --> 59:21.714
(LINE RINGING)

59:22.100 --> 59:25.092
Norman, Philip tells me you can help me.

59:25.354 --> 59:27.436
You will have my best effort, yes.

59:27.522 --> 59:29.308
Here, talk to Bill.

59:30.234 --> 59:33.522
-Norman, this is Bill.
-Is Jo still there? Can he hear me?

59:33.612 --> 59:34.772
Jo had to step out.

59:34.863 --> 59:36.854
-Let me tell you what we need.
-Okay.

59:40.786 --> 59:42.026
-State Department?
-Yes.

59:42.120 --> 59:43.576
And if Eshel can help us with that,

59:43.664 --> 59:45.700
we’ll see what we can do
about your synagogue situation.

59:45.791 --> 59:46.746
All right, I got it.

59:46.833 --> 59:48.289
Hanna, Hanna, please,

59:48.377 --> 59:50.743
just give me a minute with him on the phone.
One minute.

59:50.837 --> 59:53.670
I'm sorry, Norman. The Prime Minister
is not available to speak right now.

59:54.675 --> 59:58.042
Look, Hanna, this is a special request.

59:58.136 --> 1:00:00.513
The Prime Minister asked me
to look into it, okay?

1:00:00.597 --> 1:00:02.838
These are just very busy days for us.

1:00:02.933 --> 1:00:06.096
Unfortunately, I can't be more specific,
but I'm sure you understand.

1:00:06.186 --> 1:00:08.393
I understand, of course I understand.

1:00:08.480 --> 1:00:10.266
All right. All right, all right, all right.

1:00:10.357 --> 1:00:11.597
Please tell the Prime Minister

1:00:11.692 --> 1:00:13.853
it would be great
if we had a short conversation

1:00:13.944 --> 1:00:17.436
about a certain individual
who’s on the board of the dean’s advisory

1:00:17.531 --> 1:00:18.987
at Harvard Business School.

1:00:19.533 --> 1:00:21.444
Okay, Norman. Thank you.

1:00:21.535 --> 1:00:23.366
No, no. Thank you, Hanna.
Thank you very much.

1:00:23.453 --> 1:00:25.364
You can go back to your
very important work right now.

1:00:25.455 --> 1:00:27.616
I know, I'm sorry for interrupting you.

1:00:27.708 --> 1:00:30.370
And you're doing a greatjob.
I mean that, a really greatjob.

1:00:30.460 --> 1:00:31.711
-Thanks.
-The prime minister appreciates it.

1:00:31.795 --> 1:00:33.706
Just don't forget me.

1:00:33.797 --> 1:00:34.786
(HANNA AND DUBY SPEAKING IN HEBREW)

1:00:34.881 --> 1:00:36.087
HANNA: What do I do With him?

1:00:36.300 --> 1:00:38.666
DUBY: Norman does not get past you.
No matter what.

1:00:38.885 --> 1:00:40.170
If he gets obsessive...

1:00:40.387 --> 1:00:43.174
...take his call once every few days
so he doesn't get paranoid.

1:00:43.348 --> 1:00:45.384
HANNA: Do you think the PM
asked him for something?

1:00:45.684 --> 1:00:47.766
Isn't Davidy applying to Harvard?

1:00:47.853 --> 1:00:48.808
I don't care.

1:00:48.895 --> 1:00:50.226
Don't worry about Norman.

1:00:50.314 --> 1:00:55.604
In his head, he just had a conversation
with the Prime Minister of Israel.

1:00:55.902 --> 1:00:58.484
Yeah, I got a call
with Eshel this evening, but,

1:00:58.572 --> 1:01:01.530
you know, I brought it up with his main man,
Duby already.

1:01:01.616 --> 1:01:03.698
I think it's going to be okay. He's...

1:01:03.785 --> 1:01:05.696
He's being very practical about things.

1:01:05.787 --> 1:01:08.904
He says he can fix it,
but he wants the exact information,

1:01:08.999 --> 1:01:11.661
so if you can send me an email
with your colleague's name please...

1:01:11.752 --> 1:01:15.290
No. No e-mails, Norman.
His name is Matthias Kone.

1:01:15.380 --> 1:01:18.747
He is an official in the treasury department
in the Ivory Coast.

1:01:18.925 --> 1:01:20.836
Eshel’s ofﬁce will need to reach out to him.

1:01:20.927 --> 1:01:22.667
We are not involved.

1:01:23.764 --> 1:01:24.970
Rabbi! It's Norman.

1:01:25.057 --> 1:01:27.594
I know, I've been calling you all morning.
Why don't you answer your phone?

1:01:27.684 --> 1:01:29.299
I'm answering now.
Do you want to hear what I have to say?

1:01:29.394 --> 1:01:31.305
Yeah. You spoke to him? What did he say?

1:01:31.396 --> 1:01:34.229
Let's just say, get ready for a big surprise.

1:01:34.316 --> 1:01:36.523
How many zeros
are at the end of this surprise?

1:01:36.610 --> 1:01:38.100
-Can you tell me that at least?
-Come on.

1:01:38.236 --> 1:01:41.194
A considerable surprise. That's it.

1:01:41.281 --> 1:01:42.316
I gotta go, Rabbi.

1:01:42.407 --> 1:01:44.784
No, no, Norman, you realize
how important this is, right?

1:01:44.868 --> 1:01:46.199
We are going to get kicked out of here.

1:01:46.286 --> 1:01:48.618
You need to give us a firm answer.
No games, Norman.

1:01:48.705 --> 1:01:49.990
-Hold on. Hold...
-No time for...

1:01:50.082 --> 1:01:51.162
I can’t hear a word you’re saying.

1:01:51.249 --> 1:01:52.705
Norman ? Norman ?

1:01:53.960 --> 1:01:55.621
God damn it!

1:01:55.712 --> 1:01:57.668
How is the rabbi
connected to this again, Norman?

1:01:57.881 --> 1:01:59.496
Remind me. Why am I doing this?

1:01:59.591 --> 1:02:02.207
Do you want Rabbi Blumenthal
to marry you or not?

1:02:02.302 --> 1:02:05.214
All you have to do is you pick up the phone,

1:02:05.305 --> 1:02:09.048
call one of your buddies at Harvard
on behalf of the Prime Minister of Israel.

1:02:09.142 --> 1:02:11.007
Is that really so difficult for you?

1:02:11.103 --> 1:02:14.846
Don't belittle what I'm doing, okay?
In the world of Harvard admissions,

1:02:14.940 --> 1:02:18.432
this is the biggest no-no in the book.
It's like incest. It's taboo.

1:02:18.527 --> 1:02:22.111
That's funny, because Rabbi Blumenthal
is going to think exactly the same thing

1:02:22.197 --> 1:02:25.485
when he finds out I'm asking him
to marry a Cohen and a convert,

1:02:25.575 --> 1:02:28.157
who hasn't even officially converted.

1:02:28.495 --> 1:02:29.530
(WHISPERS) Oh, fuck.

1:02:30.038 --> 1:02:32.950
Jo, something very, very big is going on.

1:02:33.041 --> 1:02:34.542
I can't be more specific than that,

1:02:34.626 --> 1:02:35.957
but if you saw the papers this morning,

1:02:36.044 --> 1:02:37.705
you're gonna have some idea
what I'm talking about...

1:02:37.796 --> 1:02:40.287
I'm not following you, Norman.
Did you speak to him or not?

1:02:40.382 --> 1:02:43.920
No, but I’m going to read
the latest message I got from Hanna.

1:02:44.010 --> 1:02:45.090
Who is Hanna?

1:02:45.178 --> 1:02:46.384
-(L|NE RINGING)
-(CELL PHONE VIBRATING)

1:02:57.899 --> 1:02:59.639
Hanna is Duby's assistant.

1:02:59.734 --> 1:03:01.645
-BILL: Who's Duby?
-Well, that's what I'm trying to explain.

1:03:01.736 --> 1:03:02.942
(STUTTERING) Look, Eshel and Duby

1:03:03.029 --> 1:03:05.896
are now at the national security committee
as we speak,

1:03:05.991 --> 1:03:07.982
but there's no way
that I'm going to be able to get to them.

1:03:08.452 --> 1:03:10.613
Hanna, on the other hand,
is just outside that closed door.

1:03:10.704 --> 1:03:12.615
-She's gonna help us...
-Norman, cut the bullshit!

1:03:12.706 --> 1:03:16.995
When you get Eshel on the phone
then call me back when he says yes to you!

1:03:17.085 --> 1:03:18.370
Until then don't waste my time!

1:03:18.462 --> 1:03:20.123
Yeah, Jo, but this is time-sensitive.

1:03:20.213 --> 1:03:22.955
Look, I've got to tell Rabbi Blumenthal
that you're gonna give the money

1:03:23.049 --> 1:03:24.459
because someone else
is gonna buy that building...

1:03:24.551 --> 1:03:28.169
Rabbi Blumenthal is not my fucking problem!

1:03:28.263 --> 1:03:31.426
They're going to launch a war in Syria
that's gonna turn into World War III!

1:03:31.516 --> 1:03:33.757
I don't give a shit who started World War III.

1:03:33.852 --> 1:03:35.558
He's got a country to run. He's busy!

1:03:35.645 --> 1:03:37.681
Yeah, well, so am I. Goodbye, Norman!

1:03:38.899 --> 1:03:40.639
Fucking windbag.

1:03:41.026 --> 1:03:44.063
Philip, it's a call, it's a call.

1:03:44.488 --> 1:03:47.070
BLUMENTHAL: Norman, why haven’t you
returned my phone calls?

1:03:47.157 --> 1:03:48.317
PHILIP: Deliver that rabbi, Norman.

1:03:48.408 --> 1:03:51.866
Why do I get the feeling
that nothing you tell me is real?

1:03:51.953 --> 1:03:53.568
(HEAVY BREATHING)

1:03:56.458 --> 1:03:57.914
(LINE RINGING)

1:03:59.044 --> 1:04:00.659
(CELL PHONE VIBRATING)

1:04:06.259 --> 1:04:07.760
(VIBRATING)

1:04:18.355 --> 1:04:20.391
It's done. Eshel's son is on the list.

1:04:20.482 --> 1:04:22.689
You don't want to know what this cost me,
but he is on the list.

1:04:22.776 --> 1:04:25.859
Now please, if I decide to marry a camel
with three humps,

1:04:25.946 --> 1:04:28.312
-this rabbi still better be there with his tallis.
-(PANTING)

1:04:28.406 --> 1:04:30.943
Thank you, Philip.
You'll have your rabbi tomorrow.

1:04:31.034 --> 1:04:33.195
5:00 pm. I'll call you, okay?

1:04:35.455 --> 1:04:36.444
(EXHALES)

1:04:39.543 --> 1:04:40.783
(SNIFFS)

1:04:45.465 --> 1:04:46.796
(LINE RINGING)

1:04:53.139 --> 1:04:54.675
(CELL PHONE VIBRATING)

1:05:09.155 --> 1:05:10.691
(LINE CONTINUES RINGING)

1:05:23.670 --> 1:05:27.788
I might have a donor who will match

1:05:30.010 --> 1:05:32.877
your pledges up to seven million.

1:05:33.513 --> 1:05:36.425
In other words,
if you come up with seven million,

1:05:36.516 --> 1:05:38.848
half of the amount, the building's yours.

1:05:38.935 --> 1:05:40.015
I mean, ours.

1:05:40.103 --> 1:05:41.764
Who's the donor?

1:05:44.524 --> 1:05:46.560
(SIGHS) I'm sorry, I can't say.

1:05:46.651 --> 1:05:48.437
He will remain anonymous.

1:05:48.528 --> 1:05:51.315
Who donates $7 million
and wants to stay anonymous?

1:05:51.448 --> 1:05:53.188
-That doesn't make sense.
-MAN 1: What do you care?

1:05:53.325 --> 1:05:55.316
He's a modest man.
As long as he's good for it.

1:05:55.410 --> 1:05:57.025
That's a legitimate question.

1:05:57.120 --> 1:05:58.906
It's a lot of money,
we should know who the donor is.

1:05:58.997 --> 1:06:02.455
MAN 2: Do we know who this person is?
Is he sitting here right now in this room?

1:06:02.542 --> 1:06:04.203
What? Maybe this is
a money laundering scheme.

1:06:04.294 --> 1:06:06.285
I have a feeling I know
who we are talking about.

1:06:06.379 --> 1:06:07.960
Does his last name start with an R?

1:06:08.048 --> 1:06:09.037
Are we playing guessing games now?

1:06:09.132 --> 1:06:11.794
If he can say goodbye to $7 million,
why won't he just buy the whole thing?

1:06:11.885 --> 1:06:13.341
I mean, it's just a number to these people.

1:06:13.428 --> 1:06:15.009
-It's not real money.
-MAN 3: Seven million is real.

1:06:15.096 --> 1:06:17.553
MAN 4: When you get to hundreds
of millions, that's another story.

1:06:17.641 --> 1:06:20.383
BLUMENTHAL: Let's not get greedy.
This is a very generous gift.

1:06:20.477 --> 1:06:23.310
And it should motivate our entire community
to become involved.

1:06:23.396 --> 1:06:26.559
Thanks to Norman here,
we are only $7 million away

1:06:26.650 --> 1:06:28.231
from finally owning our home.

1:06:28.318 --> 1:06:30.149
But we need some kind of letter.
I mean, how do we even know

1:06:30.236 --> 1:06:31.271
-this guy exists?
-A letter of intent.

1:06:31.363 --> 1:06:32.648
-With all due respect, okay?
-We do need a letter.

1:06:32.739 --> 1:06:33.854
Some kind of written commitment...

1:06:33.948 --> 1:06:34.937
You can get us a letter, right?

1:06:35.033 --> 1:06:37.024
-A formal letter...
-It should be notarized. Should be notarized.

1:06:37.118 --> 1:06:38.233
And the money should be
in escrow.

1:06:38.328 --> 1:06:39.818
Okay. Escrow.

1:06:46.419 --> 1:06:48.796
BLUMENTHAL: You sure
you can't tell me who it is?

1:06:49.172 --> 1:06:50.537
I probably should know.

1:06:51.216 --> 1:06:52.547
I'd like to thank him.

1:06:54.844 --> 1:06:57.586
Just between you and me. Is it Arthur Taub?

1:06:59.099 --> 1:07:00.464
(CHUCKLES)

1:07:01.434 --> 1:07:04.050
He was very clear
about remaining anonymous.

1:07:08.358 --> 1:07:11.350
But, can you tell me why he is doing this?

1:07:11.444 --> 1:07:13.935
He can afford it. He knows me.

1:07:14.030 --> 1:07:17.397
I told him... I told him about the community,

1:07:17.492 --> 1:07:18.857
you know,
the history of the building, everything.

1:07:20.203 --> 1:07:22.319
And why does he insist
on remaining anonymous?

1:07:22.872 --> 1:07:27.286
If people knew he did this kind of thing,
there would be hundreds of other requests.

1:07:27.961 --> 1:07:32.045
(STUTTERING) You know,
this is not the usual

1:07:32.132 --> 1:07:35.499
type of charity that he gives to. This...

1:07:35.593 --> 1:07:37.970
This is something he did especially for me.

1:07:38.054 --> 1:07:39.294
He did it as a favor to me.

1:07:42.350 --> 1:07:45.057
Well. It is a good thing.

1:07:47.480 --> 1:07:50.267
So please thank him on behalf of all of us.

1:07:50.358 --> 1:07:51.643
Oh, yeah. Yeah.

1:07:52.485 --> 1:07:55.852
Not that raising the other half
is going to be so easy.

1:07:56.614 --> 1:07:59.230
But the challenge, it's good.

1:07:59.826 --> 1:08:02.568
-We should all open up our hearts.
-Yeah.

1:08:03.288 --> 1:08:04.403
And our wallets.

1:08:04.831 --> 1:08:07.368
God knows there are some
big wallets in this community.

1:08:07.459 --> 1:08:09.950
And if there's any way
that you think it's appropriate

1:08:10.044 --> 1:08:13.753
to honor this mysterious man, or woman,

1:08:13.840 --> 1:08:15.501
a dedication of some kind...

1:08:16.843 --> 1:08:19.209
Or if there is something
you would like me to do.

1:08:20.513 --> 1:08:23.050
Yeah, well, now that you mention it,

1:08:23.933 --> 1:08:27.391
you know, the person
who introduced me to Mr. Anonymous

1:08:27.479 --> 1:08:29.595
is actually my nephew.

1:08:29.689 --> 1:08:32.476
You know, he's a very,
very successful young lawyer.

1:08:32.567 --> 1:08:34.478
Maybe I mentioned him to you. Philip Cohen.

1:08:35.695 --> 1:08:39.313
Yeah, he's getting...
He's engaged to a very, very sweet girl.

1:08:39.407 --> 1:08:40.396
Mazel tov.

1:08:41.034 --> 1:08:42.490
From a Korean background.

1:08:45.163 --> 1:08:49.031
He might need
a little help with her conversion and

1:08:49.125 --> 1:08:50.911
officiating the wedding.

1:08:52.212 --> 1:08:53.201
Philip Cohen?

1:08:55.006 --> 1:08:57.213
If it were simple, he wouldn't need your help.

1:08:58.676 --> 1:09:00.257
(SIGHS)

1:09:02.931 --> 1:09:05.263
Have him give me a call.
I'll see what I can do.

1:09:06.059 --> 1:09:07.265
Thank you, Rabbi.

1:09:09.521 --> 1:09:10.510
Norman.

1:09:19.739 --> 1:09:21.400
(SIGHS DEEPLY)

1:09:27.747 --> 1:09:28.702
(SPEAKING HEBREW)

1:09:28.790 --> 1:09:30.326
Norman called.

1:09:31.376 --> 1:09:32.786
I should call him back.

1:09:33.211 --> 1:09:35.577
He always helps
that lump in my chest disappear.

1:09:35.880 --> 1:09:37.086
NAOMI: And I never understood why.

1:09:37.924 --> 1:09:41.883
If anything, he should make it feel worse.

1:09:42.762 --> 1:09:46.175
Why do you say that? He's a good friend.

1:09:46.599 --> 1:09:48.305
...the most generous person I know.

1:09:48.393 --> 1:09:49.382
(SCOFFS)

1:09:50.687 --> 1:09:53.269
It's naive to call him "generous."

1:09:53.648 --> 1:09:56.936
He is! He has a tremendous heart.

1:09:57.485 --> 1:09:59.225
...always eager to help.

1:10:03.241 --> 1:10:07.109
Not to say anything negative,
he's not your "friend."

1:10:07.370 --> 1:10:10.362
He's someone you take advantage of
when it's convenient.

1:10:12.500 --> 1:10:16.084
I doubt he feels that way.
That's actually pretty insulting.

1:10:16.170 --> 1:10:17.580
No. It's just the reality.

1:10:18.298 --> 1:10:21.210
When you needed him in New York,
you let him in.

1:10:21.301 --> 1:10:24.793
Now that you don't, you ignore him.

1:10:26.723 --> 1:10:27.712
(SIGHS)

1:10:27.807 --> 1:10:31.095
Now you're making that lump feel worse.

1:10:36.316 --> 1:10:39.228
You think I took advantage of him
consciously?

1:10:39.694 --> 1:10:41.434
Maybe not consciously.

1:10:43.656 --> 1:10:46.773
I believe that you consider him a friend.

1:10:46.993 --> 1:10:49.575
But the right thing to do now

1:10:49.662 --> 1:10:52.654
...is not to take any more favors from him

1:10:53.166 --> 1:10:57.125
...or from any of the other Normans
in your life.

1:11:00.256 --> 1:11:02.747
You know...

1:11:02.842 --> 1:11:07.006
you didn't protest when Norman offered
to connect us to that Harvard guy for Davidy.

1:11:09.515 --> 1:11:10.891
Right.

1:11:11.517 --> 1:11:12.893
But I was uncomfortable with it...

1:11:12.977 --> 1:11:15.559
But you went along even though
you were "uncomfortable."

1:11:16.022 --> 1:11:20.732
Honestly, I thought it was another
of his empty promises

1:11:20.944 --> 1:11:24.186
...and if that's the case, why make a fuss?

1:11:24.405 --> 1:11:26.691
Plus, you wanted Davidy to get into Harvard.

1:11:26.991 --> 1:11:29.858
...so you figured, it can't hurt.

1:11:30.244 --> 1:11:31.620
And you let it slide.

1:11:32.538 --> 1:11:34.915
-Right?
-No. Absolutely not.

1:11:35.208 --> 1:11:36.869
I thought it definitely would hurt.

1:11:37.335 --> 1:11:39.041
But I didn't want to hurt Norman's feelings.

1:11:41.881 --> 1:11:45.044
I'm glad you didn't hurt his feelings.

1:11:45.718 --> 1:11:47.549
That was very nice of you.

1:11:52.850 --> 1:11:53.976
(CLICKS SWITCH)

1:12:13.997 --> 1:12:16.739
"SOMETHING STINKS"

1:12:31.639 --> 1:12:37.555
"ESHEL FACES POLITICAL RUIN
OVER BRIBES INQUIRY"

1:12:39.480 --> 1:12:42.347
"The speculation about Eshel's future
has weakened him politically

1:12:42.442 --> 1:12:46.355
"even as he undertakes delicate negotiations
with Israel's neighbors."

1:12:46.446 --> 1:12:47.481
Well, now...

1:12:47.572 --> 1:12:50.530
Is this serious? Do we need to
worry about our peace talks next week?

1:12:50.616 --> 1:12:52.698
-DUBY: lhope not.
-Well, can we help?

1:12:53.870 --> 1:12:57.704
Maybe. Look, I don't know
who this businessman is yet,

1:12:57.790 --> 1:13:00.497
but if he's an American Citizen,
he can't testify

1:13:00.585 --> 1:13:03.577
without yourjustice department
being part of the procedure.

1:13:03.671 --> 1:13:06.162
At the moment,
this is just the press spreading rumors

1:13:06.257 --> 1:13:08.418
but let’s make sure
it doesn’t spin out of control.

1:13:08.509 --> 1:13:09.715
All right. Let me look into this.

1:13:09.802 --> 1:13:10.962
Thank you. Thank you very much, Bruce.

1:13:11.929 --> 1:13:13.635
(DUBY YELLS AND BANGS DESK)

1:13:18.478 --> 1:13:19.467
(RON SPEAKING HEBREW)

1:13:19.562 --> 1:13:23.146
The Knesset has seen
politicians with no backbone.

1:13:23.816 --> 1:13:25.397
That is not new.

1:13:25.818 --> 1:13:30.687
We've seen opportunists
distort the will of the voters.

1:13:31.574 --> 1:13:34.361
This is also not new.

1:13:35.661 --> 1:13:37.697
But never have we seen

1:13:37.789 --> 1:13:41.623
...a man so morally bankrupt

1:13:43.836 --> 1:13:46.122
...so spiritually empty

1:13:46.923 --> 1:13:49.460
...so hedonistic

1:13:50.343 --> 1:13:52.174
...selfish

1:13:52.512 --> 1:13:57.176
...in a position to do so much damage

1:13:58.184 --> 1:14:01.768
...as the man I'm pointing to right now.

1:14:01.854 --> 1:14:02.843
(GAVEL POUNDING)

1:14:12.698 --> 1:14:14.154
(SIGHS)

1:14:36.639 --> 1:14:38.470
Do you know who he is,
the New York businessman?

1:14:38.558 --> 1:14:40.970
No. If I did,
is there any way we could help Eshel?

1:14:41.060 --> 1:14:44.143
Careful, Norman. Don't put your nose
into this if you don't have to.

1:14:44.230 --> 1:14:46.892
This kind of investigation
brings out the worst in everyone.

1:14:47.275 --> 1:14:49.607
So, what do you think? How bad is this?
Is this serious?

1:14:50.486 --> 1:14:51.475
Oh, it's serious.

1:14:51.863 --> 1:14:54.696
Bribery is tricky, especially in Israel.

1:14:54.782 --> 1:14:57.398
We have the Mid-eastern mentality
of giving baksheesh

1:14:57.493 --> 1:15:01.532
and cutting corners and a legal system
run by tight-assed German yekkes.

1:15:01.622 --> 1:15:03.658
If they can prove he accepted a gift,

1:15:03.749 --> 1:15:05.785
he's done. He could end up in jail.
Look, I gotta go.

1:15:06.085 --> 1:15:07.074
Bye.

1:15:08.754 --> 1:15:09.743
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

1:15:11.841 --> 1:15:13.957
(CELL PHONE VIBRATING)

1:15:17.638 --> 1:15:18.718
(SCOFFS)
(SPEAKING HEBREW)

1:15:18.806 --> 1:15:21.263
No. He's the last thing I need today.

1:15:21.434 --> 1:15:23.174
(LINE RINGING)

1:15:48.502 --> 1:15:50.288
(LINE RINGING)

1:16:02.934 --> 1:16:03.923
ALEX: Hello?

1:16:04.477 --> 1:16:06.593
Alex. Alex Green?

1:16:06.687 --> 1:16:09.554
It's Norman, from the train.
Norman Oppenheimer.

1:16:09.649 --> 1:16:12.641
I've been meaning to call you.
How are you? How've you been?

1:16:14.695 --> 1:16:15.901
Sorry. Sorry.

1:16:17.156 --> 1:16:18.396
(CHUCKLES)

1:16:27.166 --> 1:16:28.576
I can't... I can't talk to you right now.

1:16:28.668 --> 1:16:31.751
Yes, you can. Come on down.
I'm just around the corner from you.

1:16:32.672 --> 1:16:34.082
Did you find out who it is?

1:16:34.173 --> 1:16:37.165
Better. I'm meeting the investigator
who is in Charge of the whole thing.

1:16:37.260 --> 1:16:38.716
Just come on down, right now.
Give me ﬁve minutes...

1:16:38.803 --> 1:16:40.168
-Norman, I can't...
-Bye.

1:16:54.944 --> 1:16:56.855
Thanks for coming down, really.
I appreciate it.

1:16:56.946 --> 1:16:58.607
You're acting like a maniac.

1:16:58.864 --> 1:17:01.241
Look at you. Why are you getting involved?

1:17:01.325 --> 1:17:05.238
This thing is bad for Israel, bad for America,
bad for Jews, bad for everybody. Step away...

1:17:05.329 --> 1:17:08.071
You're right, this is bad for everybody.
That's why I want to help.

1:17:08.165 --> 1:17:10.156
How can you... How can you help?

1:17:10.251 --> 1:17:13.459
This is a political war
going on 7000 miles from here.

1:17:13.546 --> 1:17:16.253
Look, Eshel's rivals
have found this cockamamie story

1:17:16.340 --> 1:17:17.955
and they're going to use it to take him down.

1:17:18.050 --> 1:17:22.384
There is nothing you can do about it.
Don't get involved. It is too big.

1:17:25.391 --> 1:17:29.009
Just one thing, though. One thing.
Just hypothetically, look...

1:17:29.103 --> 1:17:32.186
If this guy, this businessman,
he comes to you for advice,

1:17:32.273 --> 1:17:34.605
he wants you to represent him,
what are you going to tell him?

1:17:34.692 --> 1:17:36.148
You want to approach him?
That's a bad idea.

1:17:36.235 --> 1:17:38.942
No! No, I'mjust thinking maybe
we can come up with an option for him

1:17:39.030 --> 1:17:41.692
that's not so harmful to Eshel.

1:17:42.325 --> 1:17:43.906
I'd throw him out of my office.

1:17:44.327 --> 1:17:47.364
That's what I'd do.
I wouldn't want anything to do with him.

1:17:47.455 --> 1:17:49.821
He is a threat to a sitting prime minister.

1:17:50.541 --> 1:17:54.409
But even if it doesn't end up
having any criminal implication...

1:17:54.503 --> 1:17:57.745
Okay? Apparently his dealings with Eshel
are embarrassing enough

1:17:57.840 --> 1:18:01.583
so that his political rivals
think they can use him to hurt Eshel.

1:18:02.928 --> 1:18:05.465
Eshel's people can't ignore that.
They have too much to lose.

1:18:06.265 --> 1:18:07.926
They're going to strike back.

1:18:08.601 --> 1:18:11.217
Dig up everything they can find on this guy.
The FBI will get involved...

1:18:11.312 --> 1:18:14.349
I mean, no matter how you look at it,
this guy is fucked.

1:18:14.440 --> 1:18:16.897
And you want to avoid him like the plague.

1:18:21.489 --> 1:18:26.825
Look, I'm just asking if there's
some legal way to defuse this whole thing?

1:18:39.256 --> 1:18:42.874
Okay, all right.
Norman. Now you listen to me.

1:18:45.096 --> 1:18:49.465
Whoever this unnamed businessman is,
he is in very serious trouble.

1:18:52.520 --> 1:18:55.432
