As long as my head's above water...

1:37:03.776 --> 1:37:06.438
You are a good swimmer.
(CHUCKLES) That's for sure.

1:37:14.621 --> 1:37:17.363
Look, Iwish I could've
been more helpful but...

1:37:18.249 --> 1:37:20.581
-You know, I...
-You’ve been a very big help, Philip.

1:37:22.420 --> 1:37:24.581
Thank you. I appreciate it.

1:37:27.342 --> 1:37:28.673
I/ove you.

1:38:11.594 --> 1:38:14.210
Excuse me. Can I help you?

1:38:14.305 --> 1:38:15.681
Rabbi!

1:38:15.765 --> 1:38:16.800
You!

1:38:18.142 --> 1:38:19.643
(SCOFFS)

1:38:20.311 --> 1:38:21.721
What are you doing?

1:38:21.813 --> 1:38:23.553
I need to talk to you.

1:38:23.648 --> 1:38:26.811
No, you need to Sign those escrow papers,
that's what you need.

1:38:27.277 --> 1:38:29.268
Do you realize
we're going to lose all our pledges?

1:38:29.362 --> 1:38:32.149
Not to mention this building, and myjob!

1:38:33.324 --> 1:38:35.610
Norman, why haven't you
returned my phone calls?

1:38:40.498 --> 1:38:41.533
Oh, fuck!

1:38:43.001 --> 1:38:45.333
-l'm working on it.
-FuCk!

1:38:47.630 --> 1:38:49.621
I should've known not to trust you!

1:38:51.342 --> 1:38:52.331
What am I going to do now?

1:38:53.428 --> 1:38:55.589
Was there ever a donor? At any point?

1:38:55.680 --> 1:38:57.887
Yeah, but I thought I had someone.

1:38:57.974 --> 1:38:59.680
I still might have them, ljust...

1:39:04.480 --> 1:39:05.936
It's not a sure thing.

1:39:06.024 --> 1:39:08.390
Then why
would you tell us you had a donor?

1:39:09.444 --> 1:39:10.900
Why? Why would you do that?

1:39:34.927 --> 1:39:36.212
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

1:39:36.387 --> 1:39:37.888
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1:39:55.657 --> 1:39:56.646
(EXHALES)

1:39:56.741 --> 1:39:58.481
(LINE RINGING)

1:40:05.458 --> 1:40:06.868
Is that you, Norman?

1:40:11.798 --> 1:40:14.084
Norman, are you there?

1:40:16.761 --> 1:40:18.877
Is it safe for us to talk?

1:40:19.389 --> 1:40:20.879
It probably isn’t.

1:40:22.684 --> 1:40:24.174
But there’s something I need to tell you

1:40:24.268 --> 1:40:26.884
before the lawyers
and the PR people take over.

1:40:26.979 --> 1:40:30.563
And I’m speaking to you now as Micha Eshel,

1:40:30.650 --> 1:40:32.891
not as the Prime Minister of Israel.

1:40:37.448 --> 1:40:38.699
I'm sorry.

1:40:40.410 --> 1:40:42.992
I'm sorry for what is about to happen to you.

1:40:44.330 --> 1:40:47.072
In the next couple of days,
you're going to hear me say things

1:40:47.166 --> 1:40:49.248
that I don't really believe.

1:40:49.961 --> 1:40:50.950
Things about you.

1:40:53.297 --> 1:40:56.835
And it Will hurt. It Will hurt both of us.

1:40:56.926 --> 1:40:59.338
But the only reason
I will be saying these things

1:40:59.429 --> 1:41:03.217
is because there are
hundreds of thousands of lives at stake.

1:41:04.642 --> 1:41:06.348
The enemies of peace

1:41:06.436 --> 1:41:10.145
have decided to step all over you
on their way to behead me.

1:41:13.317 --> 1:41:15.569
It is a terrible price to pay.

1:41:15.653 --> 1:41:16.642
But, Norman,

1:41:18.281 --> 1:41:20.067
I can’t let them win.

1:41:21.159 --> 1:41:23.024
We can’t let them win.

1:41:25.246 --> 1:41:29.159
History is full of anonymous heroes, Norman.

1:41:32.128 --> 1:41:35.871
The day I walk up to that podium
to sign the peace treaty,

1:41:37.008 --> 1:41:40.000
you will see
a very speciﬁc expression on my face.

1:41:44.849 --> 1:41:48.967
Know that I will be thinking of you...

1:41:50.188 --> 1:41:51.974
Norman Oppenheimer.

1:41:57.945 --> 1:42:00.152
Do you accept my apology, Norman?

1:42:02.533 --> 1:42:04.034
Do you forgive me?

1:42:15.171 --> 1:42:17.127
I will never betray you.

1:42:20.927 --> 1:42:22.417
I love you, Norman.

1:42:24.013 --> 1:42:25.378
Thank you.

1:43:17.275 --> 1:43:18.310
NORMAN: Good morning, Bill.

1:43:19.151 --> 1:43:20.140
Oh...

1:43:22.780 --> 1:43:23.940
Why do you do this?

1:43:25.116 --> 1:43:27.152
Why can't anything ever be simple with you?

1:43:27.243 --> 1:43:29.108
Who says simple is good?

1:43:29.662 --> 1:43:32.244
I have a business opportunity for Jo.
He's going to like this.

1:43:32.331 --> 1:43:35.368
No. No, you don't.
Whatever it is, it's too small.

1:43:45.011 --> 1:43:46.296
Norman.

1:43:46.971 --> 1:43:47.960
Wait.

1:43:50.266 --> 1:43:52.632
I'm listening out of respect to my father.

1:43:54.103 --> 1:43:55.809
You knew him, didn't you?

1:43:58.983 --> 1:44:00.769
All right. What have you got?

1:44:03.821 --> 1:44:07.939
If you knew with 100 percent certainty

1:44:08.034 --> 1:44:11.322
that the witness who is
trying to topple down Prime Minister Eshel

1:44:11.412 --> 1:44:13.152
will never testify,

1:44:14.540 --> 1:44:16.531
would you know
how to make money with that information?

1:44:19.378 --> 1:44:22.245
Well, it depends on
where and how I got that information

1:44:22.340 --> 1:44:23.500
and if I can verify it.

1:44:23.591 --> 1:44:25.673
You realize
you're not a very reliable source, right?

1:44:26.218 --> 1:44:28.800
You put me in a room with Jo Wilf.

1:44:28.888 --> 1:44:30.753
I'll give him all the certainty he needs.

1:44:33.351 --> 1:44:35.433
Think about it. Go ahead. Think about it.

1:44:36.354 --> 1:44:38.140
Run the numbers, do the whole thing.

1:44:39.190 --> 1:44:41.306
You have until 8:00 am. to call me back.

1:44:41.984 --> 1:44:44.851
-After that, I'm going to Arthur Taub.
-(EXHALES SHARPLY)

1:44:52.203 --> 1:44:53.534
What's your fee?

1:46:37.308 --> 1:46:38.297
(EXHALES)

1:46:38.392 --> 1:46:40.303
BLUMENTHAL: Philip. Nico/e.

1:46:40.644 --> 1:46:43.886
At times like this,
when we're aware of our blessings,

1:46:43.981 --> 1:46:46.814
we also know that the world
is in desperate need of repair.

1:46:47.651 --> 1:46:51.360
Tradition explains
the act of breaking the glass

1:46:51.447 --> 1:46:54.405
reminds us to turn our hearts
towards the City of Jerusalem.

1:46:54.492 --> 1:46:57.859
In which the ultimate peace
shall be granted to the world.

1:46:59.914 --> 1:47:01.120
-Mazel tov!
-(APPLAUSE)

1:47:27.066 --> 1:47:28.272
Thank you.

1:47:31.028 --> 1:47:33.189
Welcome to Harvard, David Eshel.

1:47:33.280 --> 1:47:34.986
Thank you. Happy to be here.

1:47:41.205 --> 1:47:42.741
REPORTER: As we turn to
the economic implications

1:47:42.832 --> 1:47:44.072
of this peace treaty this morning,

1:47:44.166 --> 1:47:47.033
one investor, Jo Wilf,
is looking like a big winner.

1:47:47.128 --> 1:47:50.461
And when I say big winner, I mean, like,
a-bi/Iion-dol/ars-overnight big winner.

1:47:50.548 --> 1:47:53.460
Wilf, at a series of what now
seem like pretty prescient bets that...

1:47:53.551 --> 1:47:55.212
All the way back to the conversation
we’ve been having

1:47:55.302 --> 1:47:58.169
about the possible impeachment
of Israel’s Prime Minister.

1:47:58.264 --> 1:48:01.427
Now, just when everyone thought
the Prime Minister would get the boot,

1:48:01.517 --> 1:48:03.303
Wilf bets the opposite.

1:48:03.394 --> 1:48:06.181
He shorts natural gas
and then he magically buys shares

1:48:06.272 --> 1:48:09.389
